article.description: Shaquille O'Neal scored 32 points Friday night in the Lakers' 99-91 victory over Seattle.
article.headline: Bryant injured in first minute of game
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kobe Bryant hurt his right shoulder again, meaning the Los Angeles Lakers may not have their All-Star cast back together as soon as they believed. Shaquille O'Neal took over after Bryant went out in the game's first minute, scoring 32 points Friday night in a 99-91 victory over Seattle. The severity of Bryant's injury wasn't immediately known. Although Bryant left the arena to have an MRI shortly after colliding with Seattle's Reggie Evans, coach Phil Jackson said the results of the tests probably won't be available until Saturday. "I think it had to do with coordinating somebody to be at the hospital, to get the radiologist to the hospital and so on," Jackson explained. "We're concerned, but hopefully he'll be OK." O'Neal, who had eight rebounds, six assists and went 12-of-20 from the line, said he certainly hopes Bryant is OK. "He's a tough guy and I know he doesn't want to miss any more games," O'Neal said. "Hopefully he'll be right back." The Lakers' Gary Payton, who left the floor with a mild neck strain late in the third quarter but returned in the fourth, said it's too soon to be overly concerned about Bryant's injury. "We're not going to worry a lot about him right now. It will probably just be sore tomorrow, then he'll be fine," said Payton, who had 16 points, seven rebounds and seven assists. The Lakers' quartet of O'Neal, Bryant, Payton and Karl Malone has played together in only 21 of the team's 61 games. Malone is working his way back from a knee injury and is expected to miss at least two more games. Bryant underwent surgery on his right shoulder this past offseason, and also missed six games earlier this year after he sprained it on Jan. 12 in a collision with Cleveland's Kedrick Brown. Seattle reserve Ronald Murray had 28 points, and Ray Allen scored 19 as the Sonics lost for the sixth time in seven games. "We had it. We had the game," Murray said. "A lot of turnovers at the end of the game hurt us. Not finishing close games, making mistakes toward the end, turning the ball over, it's been a problem." Devean George's 58-footer at the buzzer ending the first quarter brought a roar from the crowd and gave the Lakers a 28-22 lead. Los Angeles remained ahead until Vitaly Potapenko hit a layup to tie it at 88-all with 3:31 to play. But Kareem Rush hit a 3-pointer with 1:32 left after O'Neal made one of two free throws, and the Lakers clinched it with four free throws by Derek Fisher and two by Luke Walton in the final 19 seconds. Bryant missed seven games with a cut on his right index finger after he accidentally put his hand through a glass window Jan. 29 while moving boxes in his garage. His surgery following last season was to repair a tear in the tissue around the right shoulder. He hurt it making a dunk last April 22 during a first-round playoff game against Minnesota, but still played the Lakers' final 10 games.

Game notes
Malone is expected to miss Sunday's game at home against New Jersey, and Monday's against his former Jazz teammates at Utah. He will make the trip to Utah, but said he didn't want to get into the game unless he played at least 15 minutes or so, which seems unlikely. "The most important thing is to be all the way back," he said. Jackson said Malone's not ready to play yet. Malone tore a ligament in his right knee Dec. 21 and landed on the injured list for the first time in his career. ... Los Angeles C Horace Grant is out with a strained hip flexor. He'll be reevaluated next week.
